{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:22:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:22:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12277"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12277"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0.04,0.02,0.89]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113911"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4799"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2427"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"12418"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47324"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113911"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents with a two-hour history of acute onset cough, stridor and respiratory distress. The parents state that the symptoms began suddenly approximately 30 minutes after dinner. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 120/min, respiratory rate 40/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, and oxygen saturation 90% on room air. Auscultation reveals reduced breath sounds and wheeze on the right side of the chest. There is no rash. He does not allow examination of his throat.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute epiglottitis","Croup","Anaphylaxis","Bronchiolitis","Inhaled foreign body"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe child most likely has an \u003Cstrong\u003Einhaled foreign body\u003C/strong\u003E, based on the sudden onset of choking, coughing and respiratory distress. The unilateral reduced breath sounds and wheeze are particularly suggestive. Foreign body aspiration peaks between ages 1-2 years when children explore objects with their mouths. The delay between dinner and symptom onset (30 minutes) is not unusual with foreign body aspiration, as small objects may initially lodge in a less obstructive position and then shift to cause more significant symptoms. Complete upper airway obstruction may require basic life support. A foreign body in the lower airway can cause air trapping, potentially leading to pneumothorax, surgical emphysema or pneumomediastinum. Inspiratory chest X-rays may appear normal, but an expiratory film can reveal air trapping.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute epiglottitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves inflammation of the epiglottis, arytenoids and aryepiglottic folds. It is associated with immunocompromised children or those with insufficient \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E type B (Hib) immunisation. Typical features include fever, malaise, severe sore throat, difficulty swallowing, drooling, and the child sitting upright with neck extended to optimise airflow. A low-pitched stridor or stertor may be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECroup\u003C/strong\u003E commonly affects younger children, causing inspiratory stridor and barking cough from viral infection of the trachea, larynx, and bronchi. Children are often febrile and unsettled but systemically well. Parainfluenza virus is the most common cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute respiratory distress and systemic features like tongue/facial swelling, urticaria, and hemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiolitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a clinical diagnosis of viral lower respiratory tract infection, usually affecting infants under 12 months old. It peaks at 2-3 days, with fever, cough, increased work of breathing, and diffuse wheeze or crackles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A sudden onset of coughing and choking in a young child may suggest foreign body aspiration.","Unilateral reduced breath sounds and wheeze are suggestive of foreign body aspiration.","Foreign body aspiration peaks between ages 1-2 years when children explore objects with their mouths."],"references":["Australian Resuscitation Council ANZCOR Guideline 4 Airway  https://resus.org.au/guidelines/","Advanced Paediatric Life Support. Algorithm for the management of the choking child https://www.apls.org.au/algorithm-choking-child"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12277"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T12:12:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T12:13:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4799"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"qu